Gall (
Figs 14–16
). Individual galls are approximately spherical, 3.5 –5.0 mm in height (n= 8 ), and integral to the leaf lamina. Galls cause swelling on both upper and lower surfaces of the leaf, and each contains a single(unilocular) thin-walled larval chamber 1.5–1.7 mm in diameter (n= 8 ), attached by a tiny filament to the outer wall of the gall. In mature galls, the larval chamber loses its connection to the gall wall, and rolls freely within an internal air space. Though galls can occur separately on a leaf, they are often aggregated into masses 20–70 mm long that distort the leaf blade. Young galls are fleshy and pale green to yellowish, remaining soft as they mature.
